<h2>Cross-Origin Limitation</h2>
<p>For security reasons, the <code>download</code> attribute is <strong>ignored on cross-origin URLs</strong>. If the link points to a different origin, the browser navigates to the URL instead of downloading. This prevents a malicious page from silently downloading files from other domains onto the user's device.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Cross-origin behavior">{{ crossOriginExample | escape }}</code-block>

<p>To enable cross-origin downloads, the server must set the <code>Content-Disposition: attachment</code> HTTP header. This is a server-side solution that works regardless of the <code>download</code> attribute.</p>

<h2>Generated Content with Blob URLs</h2>
<p>The most powerful use of <code>download</code> is with Blob URLs for client-generated content. Create the data in JavaScript, wrap it in a Blob, generate a temporary URL, and trigger a download — no server round-trip required.</p>

